Diagnosis: Males can be easily recognised by the fine embolus with a narrow base, complete coil and tip directed distally and slightly retrolaterally (
Fig. 163
). Females have an epigyne with copulatory openings that are curved towards the posterior, situated laterally of the lateral margins of the spermathecae, with relatively long, nearly transverse copulatory ducts (
Fig. 172
).

Distribution: Known only from three localities in central Africa (
Fig. 182
).
